# Clerk Auth: Data Isolation

Every server action and API route that touches the database **must** verify the caller's identity with Clerk and scope all queries to that user. Never trust a user-supplied ID for ownership checks.

## Pattern

```ts
import { auth } from "@clerk/nextjs/server";
import { db } from "@/lib/db";
import { decks, cards } from "@/lib/schema";
import { eq, and } from "drizzle-orm";

// ✅ GOOD — always get userId from Clerk, never from params/body
const { userId } = await auth();
if (!userId) return new Response("Unauthorized", { status: 401 });

// ✅ GOOD — scope every query with clerkUserId
const userDecks = await db.select().from(decks).where(eq(decks.clerkUserId, userId));

// ✅ GOOD — for child resources (cards), join through the parent deck
const card = await db
  .select()
  .from(cards)
  .innerJoin(decks, eq(cards.deckId, decks.id))
  .where(and(eq(cards.id, cardId), eq(decks.clerkUserId, userId)));

if (!card.length) return new Response("Not Found", { status: 404 });
```

```ts
// ❌ BAD — trusting caller-supplied userId
const { userId } = params; // attacker can supply any ID
const userDecks = await db.select().from(decks).where(eq(decks.clerkUserId, userId));

// ❌ BAD — fetching a deck by ID without checking ownership
const deck = await db.select().from(decks).where(eq(decks.id, deckId));
```

## Rules

- Always call `auth()` (server) at the top of every route/action; reject immediately if `userId` is falsy.
- `decks` has a `clerkUserId` column — filter it on every query.
- `cards` and `cardReviews` have no direct `clerkUserId`; reach ownership through `decks` via a join or a sub-query.
- `cardReviews` has its own `clerkUserId` — always filter it as well.
- Never expose another user's data even if the request contains a valid-looking resource ID.
